[1] Cholera - Nigeria
Date: Wed, 17 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Alertnet.org [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L17718363.htm>

Cholera outbreak in Nigeria kills 42 - hospital
-----------------------------------------------
A major outbreak of cholera in northern Nigeria has killed 42 people and
hospitalized hundreds in the last 2 weeks, authorities said on Wed, 16 Nov
2004. Gravely dehydrated people lined the floors of the Infectious Diseases
Hospital in Kano as the government told doctors to treat the victims free
of charge.
"We have had 629 cases so far in the last 2 weeks of which 42 are confirmed
dead," said Ashiru Rajab, the hospital's chief medical officer. More than
1600 Africans have been killed so far in 2004 by cholera, an intestinal
infection spread by contaminated food and water, WHO said.
******
[2] Cholera - Uganda
Date: Tue, 16 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The Monitor(Kampala) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200411160725.html>

Cholera reported in Kitgum
--------------------------
The suspected cholera outbreak which was reported recently has been
confirmed, the director of health services, Dr Vincent Oringa, has said. He
was addressing stakeholders and the cholera emergency committee on Fri 12
Nov 2004.
Oringa confirmed the existence of cholera in Akilok parish, in Orom
sub-county, a settlement camp with a population of 2442 people, comprising
77 households. It is located 56 miles north east of Kitgum.
Cholera had been suspected in the area after a number of bloody diarrhea
and other symptomatic dehydration cases were reported. 2 deaths and
specimens taken to Kampala for testing confirmed the disease. A cholera
Force Committee has been formed to contain the situation and control its
spread to other areas.
[byline: Odoki Okella]
******
[3] Cholera - Uganda
Date: Mon, 15 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Alertnet.org [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/a2ab0b61898cf2c5449c90020649d20b.htm>

Cholera cases reach 56 in IDP camp
----------------------------------
The number of cholera cases reported among residents of Pabbo [internal]
displaced persons (IDP) camp in the northern Ugandan district of Gulu
reached 56, including 3 deaths in Oct 2004, WHO reported.
43 cholera patients had been treated at a health facility in the camp and
discharged by 28 Oct 2004 and 10 were still receiving treatment, the WHO
said in an update issued on 10 Nov 2004.
The 1st case of the epidemic was a man who has been in the camp without
visiting another place for a long time. He fell sick and was admitted in
Pabbo health center III with pneumonia on 3 Oct 2004 and he was about to be
discharged after improvement when he developed profuse diarrhea and
vomiting, and later died. The other 2 deaths occurred outside the
health-care settings.
Pabbo IDP camp is the largest and has a population of over 64 000 people.
The camps were set to accommodate people who could not continue to live in
their villages because of fighting between government forces and rebels of
the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA). According to WHO, measures taken to curb
the spread of the disease include the setting up of a temporary cholera
treatment centre with isolation facilities, social mobilization of the
community towards containment of the epidemic through encouraging personal,
food and environmental hygiene using community resource persons, local FM
radio and community talks by the health workers and leaders.
Water chlorination began after tests found that all water pots in
households, 2 out of 14 boreholes and all 6 springs were contaminated. Oral
rehydration therapy sites were established in the camp to handle mild cases
of diarrhea and 2 large tents were set up to handle more cases, should the
need arise.
Cholera control measures were, however, being hampered by the recent heavy
rains that had worsened sanitary conditions, according to WHO. Supplies to
control the epidemic were still insufficient, the agency added.
