[6] Cholera - Senegal
Date: Thu, 18 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: IOL.co.za [edited]
<http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?art_id=qw1100695685100S524&set_id=1&click_id=6&sf=>

Cholera outbreak seems to be slowing in Dakar
---------------------------------------------
An outbreak of cholera in the West African state of Senegal appeared to be
slowing, health authorities said, with no cases of the waterborne illness
reported since 10 Nov 2004.
"The situation appears to be improving," said Doctor Bassirou Johnson of
the epidemiology division of the Senegalese health ministry. "We have seen
some suspect cases but they turned out to be false alarms."
6 people have died and 855 treated since mid-October 2004 for the
waterborne illness that spreads due to poor hygiene and sanitation.
The outbreak was 1st registered in one of the poorer neighborhoods in
Dakar, a cramped coastal town of dirty streets and limited fresh water
supplies.
The government has moved quickly to contain the outbreak, sending medicine
and equipment to even the most remote quarters to curb its transmission and
launching major disinfection campaigns in public markets and bus stations
and aboard the shared transport vehicles that ply the roads.
Cholera is a deadly but preventable disease that is generally contracted
from polluted water supplies and manifests itself in violent diarrhoea and
sometimes fatal dehydration.
This is the 1st cholera epidemic in Senegal since 1997. The last major
outbreak in the country was in 1995-97.
