[7] Cholera - India
Date: Mon, 15 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: New India Press [edited]
<http://www.newindpress.com/Newsitems.asp?ID=IET20041114124016&Title=Southern+News+-+Tamil+Nadu&Topic=0>

40 cholera cases confirmed in city
----------------------------------
As many as 40 patients admitted to Communicable Diseases Hospital (CDH) at
Tondiarpet have tested positive for cholera. Around 282 patients, mostly
from North Chennai, were admitted to the CDH in the past week with symptoms
of the disease.
While 32 more were admitted on Sun, 14 Nov 2004, on complaints of vomiting,
diarrhea and symptoms of dehydration, the Chennai Corporation said that the
number of suspected cholera cases reported at the hospital has decreased
considerably.
Some of the patients admitted 4 days ago were discharged on Sun, 14 Nov
2004, after treatment. Others are reported to be out of danger.
Local administration minister K P Anbazhagan along with Law Minister D
Jayakumar and Chennai Corporation deputy mayor "Karate" R Thiagarajan
visited the patients and asked the hospital authorities to take all
possible steps to prevent the disease from spreading further. Anbazhagan
instructed the Corporation officials to convene health camps in Tondiarpet
and Pulianthope zones, particularly in areas like Vysarpadi, Washermenpet
and Korukkupet, which are more affected.
According to officials, overflow of sewage, stagnation of sewage-mixed rain
water besides sewage water entering into drinking water pipes were the main
reasons for the outbreak.
******
[8] Diarrhea, fatal - Indonesia (Sumatra)
Date: Tue, 16 Nov 2004
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@ntlworld.com>
Source: The Jakarta Post/Padang [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/detailnational.asp?fileid=20041117.C03&irec=2>

An outbreak of diarrhea has been plaguing Solok municipality, West Sumatra,
since last week, leaving at least 4 people dead and 217 others hospitalized
at one stage or another, local officials said on Tue, 16 Nov 2004.
Solok health office director Azwar Hijar said the victims had died in
separate hospitals, or before arriving at the hospital, from serious
dehydration after not seeking medical treatment in time.
The 4 dead victims were 2 adults aged 49 and 52 and 2 children aged 9 and
1.5 years. They died between 9 and 13 Nov 2004, when the diarrhea outbreak
was at its height.
Azwar said at least 217 other sufferers had been hospitalized in the Solok
General Hospital and the local military hospital, but most had been allowed
to return home. "There are currently only 30 diarrhea patients being
treated in the 2 hospitals. They were admitted on Sun, 14 Nov 2004," he added.
Azwar said the diarrhea outbreak was probably due to contaminated drinks or
food prepared using contaminated seaweed. According to Azwar, some of the
victims said that they had suffered cramps and started vomiting after
consuming beverages they had bought in Bareh traditional market in the city.
"We have yet to determine the type of bacteria. We have taken samples of
vomit and excrement from the patients for tests at the West Sumatra Health
Laboratory in Pangilun, Padang. It will take a week for the results," Azwar
added. He said most of the victims had probably been infected when they
took their relatives suffering from diarrhea to the hospital, or visited
them there.
"We suspect they picked up the bug from patients in the hospital as people
stopped consuming iced seaweed and drinks from Bareh market after 9 Nov
2004, the first day of the diarrhea outbreak," Azwar explained.
He said the Solok health office was opening a center that would be open
around the clock to handle the outbreak, adding that it would provide data,
information and guidance, as well as medicine, for local people.
Azwar said his office on Mon, 15 Nov 2004, had distributed around 800
bottles of rehydration fluid and 7000 tetracycline capsules, which had been
provided by the West Sumatra health office.
--
Pablo Nart
<p.nart@ntlworld.com>
[This episode may well be cholera. - Mod.LL]
