[9] Cholera - Fiji
Date: Wed, 17 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Fiji Times [edited]
<http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=11745>

Friendly cholera found in resort
--------------------------------
A strain of cholera found in a resort was not deadly, health officials
said. On Thu 9 Nov 2004 an Australian tourist was admitted to hospital on
returning home from a holiday at the Plantation Island Resort in Aug 2004.
Health Ministry chief executive Lepani Waqatakirewa said there were 2 types
of bacteria which could cause cholera. "One is the harmful hemolytic strain
which causes cholera and the other is associated as a friendly bacteria and
is non-hemolytic," he said.
"Bacteria found on Plantation Island was non-hemolytic but health officials
responded to the threat by isolating the area and workers and gave guests
preventive measures."
Mr Waqatakirewa said cholera was mostly found in outer islands and the
Northern Division. "It is common where marine life is rich and fish is
taken from waters which are contaminated.
[The presence or absence of hemolysis in _V. cholerae_ does not necessarily
distinguish pathogenic strains of the organism from nonpathogenic ones. The
classical biotype of the cholera bacillus is nonhemolytic and certainly can
cause overt cholera. Hemolysis can be found in the El Tor biotype and,
historically, this has been used to distinguish the biotypes.
Strains of El Tor that do not produce hemolysis have been reported, and
some strains of both O1 and O139 _V. cholerae_ which are not hemolytic
initially can be hemolytic after serial passage through rabbit ideal loops.
The usefulness of hemolysis as a virulence factor is unclear, since
nonhemolytic strains produce fluid accumulation in the rabbit gut, and
hemolytic strains do not necessarily produce a secretory response.
Ref: Singh DV, Matte MH, Jiang S, et al. Molecular analysis of Vibrio
cholerae O1, O139, non-O1, and non-O139 strains: clonal relationships
between clinical and environmental isolates. App Environ Microbiol 2001;
67: 910-21. - Mod.LL]
